    <string name="info_screen_title">Glycemic Index</string>
    <string name="info_ig_1">At a nutritional level, the glycemic index (GI) is one more characteristic of each of the foods that we include in our diet. It is a simple measure to understand how quickly the carbohydrates we eat (sugars) are transformed into glucose in the blood. It is an important concept, as pointed out by the Fundación para la Diabetes (FD), because this index can make some foods recommended in certain circumstances and be inadvisable in others.</string>
    <string name="info_ig_2">Remember that one of the macronutrients that food contains is carbohydrates (sugars), which can be rapidly absorbed (simple carbohydrates) or somewhat slower (compound carbohydrates). That amount of sugar and how quickly our body absorbs it is the glycemic index. In an imaginary table, the maximum GI would have a value of 100 and would correspond to glucose itself, that is, sugar. Then we have three segments in which the different foods can be included according to their composition:</string>
    <string name="info_ig_3">High GI: 70 or more</string>
    <string name="info_ig_4">Medium or moderate GI: 55 - 69</string>
    <string name="info_ig_5">Low GI: 54 or less</string>

